Keras

The general workflow for building a Keras model

  1. Prepare data
    • Balancing, scaling, training and test
  2. Define model
    • Hyperparameters
    • Architecture
    • Compile
  3. Train model
  4. Evaluate model

Walk through of the Iris example using Keras

1. Prepare data

  • Balancing
iris %>% count(Species)
##      Species  n
## 1     setosa 50
## 2 versicolor 50
## 3  virginica 50

1. Prepare data

  • Scaling, training (80%) and test (20%)
nn_dat <- iris %>%
  as_tibble %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, scale) %>%
  mutate(Species_num = as.numeric(Species) - 1,
         data_type = sample(x = c("train", "test"), size = nrow(.),
                            replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.80, 0.20))) %>% 
  sample_n(size = nrow(.))
nn_dat

1. Prepare data

  • Data matrices and target vectors
X_train <- nn_dat %>% filter(data_type == "train") %>% select(matches("Sepal|Petal")) %>% as.matrix
y_train <- nn_dat %>% filter(data_type == "train") %>% pull(Species_num) %>% to_categorical
X_test <- nn_dat %>% filter(data_type == "test") %>% select(matches("Sepal|Petal")) %>% as.matrix
y_test <- nn_dat %>% filter(data_type == "test") %>% pull(Species_num) %>% to_categorical
X_train %>% head(3)

2 Define model

  • Hyperparameters - Are they all familiar by now?
n_input     <- ncol(X_train)
n_hidden_1  <- 4
h1_activate <- "relu"
n_output    <- 3
o_ativate   <- "softmax"
n_epochs    <- 200
batch_size  <- 20
loss_func   <- "categorical_crossentropy"
learn_rate  <- 0.001
optimizer   <- optimizer_rmsprop(learning_rate = learn_rate)

2 Define model

  • Architecture
model <- keras_model_sequential() %>% 
  layer_dense(units = n_hidden_1, activation = h1_activate, input_shape = n_input) %>% 
  layer_dense(units = n_output, activation = o_ativate)
model %>% summary
## Model: "sequential"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## Layer (type)                        Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
## dense_1 (Dense)                     (None, 4)                       20          
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## dense (Dense)                       (None, 3)                       15          
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 35
## Trainable params: 35
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________

2 Define model

  • Compile model
model %>%
  compile(loss = loss_func,
          optimizer = optimizer,
          metrics = c("accuracy")
)

3. Train model

  • Train model
history <- model %>%
  fit(x = X_train,
      y = y_train,
      epochs = n_epochs,
      batch_size = batch_size,
      validation_split = 0.2,
      verbose = FALSE
)

3. Train model

  • Inspect training progress (one epoch = one run through the entire data)
history %>% plot

4. Evaluate model

  • Test performance
model %>% evaluate(X_test, y_test)
##      loss  accuracy 
## 0.3361526 0.9230769
  • Training performance
model %>% evaluate(X_train, y_train)
##      loss  accuracy 
## 0.2811423 0.9639640
